languages.text:
The Children of Quetza Temer: Chronicles{br}
An analysis of the canvases made from wood bast fibre showed that the chronicle has been recorded for at least five hundred years. The older chronicles tell of a bleak historical period of the tribe's decline due to an unknown virus. The symbols on the canvas resemble High Gothic letters, but the inhabitants do not know the origin of their meaning, claiming that the sacred knowledge was bestowed upon them by Quetza Temer himself. This character, revered as a god, obviously originates from the Imperium that we know, his exact name either lost or adapted in accordance with local phonetics. The only other sacred symbol the tribe reveres is the Aquila — the "Two-Headed Eagle-God."
A group of the most interesting canvases depicting tragic, yet heroic deeds, was confiscated and taken on board for further investigation. Many of the words made up from the scrambled Gothic symbols were easy to decipher, such as "banished," "sacrifice," "valley" (or "land"/"lands"), as well as "death," "incomprehensible," and "merciful." This part most likely talks about some sort of sacrificial pilgrimage.
A priest has confirmed my theory: any tribesmen who have committed an offence can atone by sacrificium — a journey to the Deadlands, full of "unknown deaths."
The Adepts that I have sent to investigate the Deadlands have not returned yet.{br}
End of log.

